{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649564"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:04:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:04:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18366"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18366"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11084"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74383"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11084"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59875"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7418"},{"type":"tags","id":"7466"},{"type":"tags","id":"7470"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25706"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25710"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74383"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the sustentaculum tali?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A bony prominence on the medial side of the calcaneus that supports the talus","A nerve that innervates the plantar aspect of the foot","A tendon that stabilises the lateral aspect of the ankle","A muscle that flexes the toes","A ligament that connects the talus to the navicular bone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esustentaculum tali\u003C/strong\u003E is a bony prominence on the medial side of the calcaneus. It serves as a support for the talus, helping to stabilise the ankle joint. This structure is important in maintaining the alignment and function of the foot and ankle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eligament that connects the talus to the navicular bone\u003C/strong\u003E is the talonavicular ligament, which is part of the spring ligament complex and plays a role in maintaining the arch of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etendon that stabilises the lateral aspect of the ankle\u003C/strong\u003E is likely referring to the peroneal tendons, which run along the lateral side of the ankle and help with eversion of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emuscle that flexes the toes\u003C/strong\u003E includes the flexor digitorum longus and flexor hallucis longus, which are not related to the sustentaculum tali.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enerve that innervates the plantar aspect of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E is the tibial nerve, which branches into the medial and lateral plantar nerves, providing sensation and motor function to the sole of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The sustentaculum tali is a bony structure on the calcaneus that supports the talus.","It serves as an attachment point for ligaments and tendons, contributing to the stability of the ankle joint.","Understanding the anatomy of the sustentaculum tali is important for diagnosing and managing foot and ankle injuries."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59875"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18366"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59875"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T05:00:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-24T09:36:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11084"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74383"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"da